To verify the prediction that chelate functionalized CDs can specifically recognize metal ions, we established a functional relationship with Origin software. lgK of EDTA or HEDP to different metal ions as X-axis, degree of fluorescence quenching (1-F/F

                           0
                        ) of EfCDs or HfCDs as Y-axis. Finally, exponential type functions were obtained.

CDs with tailor-made chelating ligands were synthesized by free radical polymerization in combination of hydrothermal carbonization technology. EDTA and HEDP chelating ligands functionalized CDs achieved directional conversion of the precursors, resulting in the high synthetic yields of 86.7% and 72.5%, respectively. Additionally, chelate functionalized CDs can realize specific recognition of metal ions. Based on the strong metal-chelating affinity of EDTA and HEDP for Fe3+ and Cu2+ (lgKEDTA-Fe = 25.1, lgKHEDP-Cu = 12.5), we have predicted and confirmed EfCDs and HfCDs have specific recognition ability for Fe3+ and Cu2+, respectively. Additionally, the exponential type functions between coordination constant (lgK) and fluorescence quenching degree (1-F/F

                        0
                     ) of EfCDs or HfCDs for different metal ions were established, which promotes the prediction of metal ion specific recognition. This strategy offered an improved method for developing CDs with tailor-made chelating ligands for specific metal ions recognition, which is of great significance to environmental monitoring and biomedical science.
